Sir, I think it is bit of a truncated Judgment and I am also baffled by it since the Constitution states that Parliament has control over public finance. However, I am not in any way saying that the people who have filed the cases have no right to file those and of course, the learned Supreme Court Judges have their own right to express their opinion. But, I feel this is not the right time - I am only looking at it from a political angle - for such a Judgment as it would only divide the country. And also to decide that only one person or a certain number of persons are responsible, the actions they had taken are arbitrary and those aggravated the economic situation, I do not think is a very fair Judgment. We know that there are root causes for this. The COVID-19 pandemic was one of the root causes. Also, there have been other countries which have become bankrupt due to certain policies implemented at that time, including the Modern Monetary Theory. That was implemented not only in Sri Lanka, but in other countries, too. So, to decide that the decisions and policies which were carried out at that time are arbitrary, I do not think is a fair Judgment. It is a 300-page Judgment and I have not read the entirety of it. The Court also went on to hold, I quote from the Judgment:

that administrative acts and decisions contrary to public trust would be in excess and/or abuse of power by the Executive and therefore, violative of the fundamental rights in general and Article 12(1) of the Constitution in particular, which guarantees equality before the law and equal protection of the law.
The administrative acts and decisions, Sir, are the policy decisions. The administrative acts are policy decisions put into action and that is a right of the Executive.
Then, Article 12(1) is not pertaining to an individual.The Judgment further states, I quote:

"These petitioners both in applications SC FR 195/2022 and SC FR 212/2022 have invoked the fundamental rights jurisdiction of this Court in the interest of the public. We note that none of the petitioners are claiming any loss had impacted on the petitioners on an individual basis but their assertion is as a result of the conduct of the respondents the entire citizenry had to undergo hardships which could have been avoided."
Sir, I hope we would have a debate on this Judgment later on.

RESTITUTION OF AMPARA, THOTTASURUNKI PADDY LAND

( ) (The Hon. Seyed Ali Zahir Moulana) Hon. Presiding Member, I stand here today to show my solidarity with my Hon. Friend who moved this Adjournment Motion. Hon. Minister, of course, all this is about land. Under the Land Development Ordinance, permits were issued to farmers for paddy lands in Thottachchurungiwaddai situated in Malwatta 02 Grama Niladhari Division in the Divisional Secretary's Division of Samanthurai in the Ampara District way back in 1964. Due to the conflict situation that prevailed in the country, the farmers who originally owned those lands were forced to vacate them, abandoning their paddy cultivation. They were displaced and left the Thottachchurungiwaddai area to other areas. Since then, people in the Uhana area have encroached the lands and continue to cultivate them to date. Even the displaced people who were resettled in their own places are unable to reclaim their abandoned paddy lands.

Later on, during the post-conflict days, they made a complaint to the LLRC - the Lessons Learnt and Reconciliation Commission - and the Commission looked into the matter. Subsequently, a mobile service was conducted. It was inquired into with the participation of the Divisional Secretary of Samanthurai, the Provincial Land Commissioner of the Eastern Province, the District Secretary and various other relevant authorities. They wanted to verify the permits of the owners, to see whether those are true ones. Subsequently, they agreed to settle the owners there. But, to date, it has not happened. So, that is the issue. This has been happening all over the Eastern Province. I represent the Batticaloa District, Hon. Minister. Even though the Panampalana Commission, way back in 2000, recommended so many things, for certain lands - more than 220 acres of land - to be given
to the newly formed Divisional Secretary's Division of Koralaipattu Central, so far, for some reason, it has not been implemented.

So, I am going to take this matter up at the Committee Stage Discussion on the Vote of the Ministry of Lands. Then, I can come up with more details on that issue. I am sure, Hon. Minister, with your guidance, these matters could be resolved amicably, calling for a meeting with these affected farmers and the relevant authorities. As early as possible, please make sure these matters are settled.
Thank you very much. ( ) (The Hon. Presiding Member) . .
